xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3728</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00MJ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00MJ.xml</fr:route><fr:title>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijective</fr:link> enumeration of the integers</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>29</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We can define a bijective enumeration of the integers by “zigzagging” between the positive and the negative following the pattern<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (0, -1, 1,-2,2,-3,3,\ldots \right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \begin {aligned}   e&\colon  \mathbb {N}\twoheadrightarrow  \mathbb {Z}\\   e{\mathopen {}\left (i\right )\mathclose {}} &=   \begin {cases}    0 &\text {when } i=0\\    i\div  2 &\text {when } i > 0 \land  2\mid  i\\    -{\mathopen {}\left (i+1\right )\mathclose {}}\div  2 &\text {when } i > 0 \land  \lnot {\mathopen {}\left (2\mid  i\right )\mathclose {}}   \end {cases}  \end {aligned} ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
